title: Quality Change?
text:
I first ordered People Socks in Jan 2020. They were amazing - super soft and comfortable. I placed two more orders in the next month.

As I have basically lived in these socks through COVID they have become a little scratchy. I didn't realize that its not the best approach to dry them in the dryer. as it changes the character of the fabric. So, I ordered more.

The new socks arrived yesterday and they just aren't the same quality as they were less than a year ago. They are tight. They are not overly soft. I will not order again.

title: No longer good!!! Don't buy!
text:
No longer good!
I thought I was going crazy, because I had been wearing these shoes for years and years and loved them, always had a pair or sometimes two handy for when the old pair's life was ending, and suddenly the same size didn't fit at all and my feet got extremely smelly and sweaty while wearing them. My old pair still fit and so did other shoes, so it had to be the shoes. But reading these reviews I know that it isn't me... Do not buy these shoes! Bad about this website: I was just chatting with an employee to ask about this issue before reading theses reviews and he told me that nothing changed when I literally asked about it. So that is no way to treat a customer, it's basically a lie... They should be honest about this change, they cheapened the production, making this a bad shoe, not what you could get before.
To top it off, I sent in this review at the Reebok website before and it was turned down for not meeting their standards. I checked, nope, it's up to standard alright. I guess Reebok is not into honest criticism? So submitting this review to amazon and other places now, I mean I took the time to write it...

title: Not good. Bad actually.
text: I wont go as low to say they are garbage, but not far off the mark. They are a little small, a little short, a lot thin, not warm and I'm not the kinda person that gets cold feet easily. Not sure what they are good for... maybe summer...no, to uncomfortable. I'm actually trying to figure out how people suffered thru wearing these long enough to develop holes in them, I couldn't get them off quick enough.  I'm thinking extra socks for the camper or tent in case all your GOOD socks get too wet or dirty these could be a last resort. Or they would make nice toilet paper in an emergency. You could store things in them I suppose. I read the poor reviews and thought, oh people are just being picky, nope they were all accurate. Someone compared them to Haynes socks but I'm pretty sure Haynes are thicker and fit better. Too bad. I really would keep looking. Unless of coarse you need some good toilet paper.

title: New product is low quality!!
text:
I have bought these socks several times over the last few years and they have always been reasonably priced and of good quality. This recent order was clearly substandard. Thinner socks with fewer loops of fabric inside than ever before. These used to be about $20 for 4 pair and were so thick it was kind of a space problem inside your dresser drawer. These new ones are thin, low quality, and not nearly as comfortable and warm as they used to be.

Such a shame, I started buying these because I wanted to support an American company. Now that company has jacked up the price and cut quality in half! Typical bait and switch that got US auto manufacturers in trouble. Build a solid reputation on quality and value, then jack up the price, cut back on quality and materials, and ride on the reputation until the wheels fall off. Very disappointing, I sent these back and won't be ordering any more from this company!!

In my photo you can ser for yourself how 4 new pair stack up against 4 old pair (about 1 year old and worn frequently!!).

title: Not what you'd expect
text: I received these today.  I have previously owned Corcoran Jump Boots.  These were made of a cheaper leather and the fit was sloppy.  There is virtually no ankle support and my foot moved freely when walking.  Aside from playing the insole/heel cup game there was no way to "tighten" the fit up.  They were laced (the laces are junk, too) so that each side of the eyelets were virtually touching each other which in and of itself is a sign of poor fit.  Fit as far as toe to heel is on par with other Corcoran boots so the issue is not that they are a size too large, just the upper is sized wrong.  For those that have large ankles these may fit fine if other boots are too snug.These are going back.

Severely disappointed in Reebok and Amazon.

title: Not Worth The Savings
text:
As many people here, I bought a set of People Socks based on reviews. I got the sense I was buying high-quality American-made lower-cost socks and was willing to try them out. I only wear them a couple months of the year, and mostly weekends, so they don't get heavy use. Out of the box People Socks seem decent, and I liked them so much I bought another set the following year. HERE'S THE PROBLEM:

In 2011, I bought a few Wigwam socks. See link below. They're pricey, hence my next purchases:
2013: Bought a set of People Socks
2014: Bought that second set of People Socks I mentioned earlier.

It's 2016, and guess what: as I write this review, I am wearing a pair of my original Wigwams. ALL of the People Socks I've purchased have worn through the foot and I've thrown them away. By my math I get three times the wear for only twice the cost. I'm not saying you should run out and buy Wigwams, but I CAN tell you that sometimes quality IS better than quantity.

[[ASIN:B000TA74IM Wigwam Men's Hiking/Outdoor Pro Length Sock, Charcoal, Large]]

Bonus: People Socks pill like nobody's business. Wigwams don't. Though this really only seems to be an aesthetic problem, and they mention it on the PS page, but it's worth mentioning.

title: Hot and Sweaty
text: I have worn Wolverine work boots for years. Raiders, Guardians and Legends have all been a good fit for me at a 10.5.  I thought I'd try the Overpass. The reviews were quite good and I felt good with the purchase I was making. First the 10.5 was significantly tight. I returned those and ordered the 10.5w. This fit similarly to my pair of Wolverine Legends 10.5 that are my current boot. I've tried to wear the Overpass. I've made it through 2 half days and another full day. They are hot. My feet just sweat in them. This wetness creates sore miserable feeling feet. I have been wearing my old Legends for the last 3 days and I am much happier with them. I am stuck with a pair of boots that are really unwearable for me after about 16 hours of wear. I really wish I had stuck with the Wolverine Legends for this purchase. I guess I'll live with my old Legends for a while yet. Live and Learn.

text: The first thing you notice when you get these is the truly awful smell don't open this package in the house if you don't like very powerful chemical smells. Then there's the design, these have no way for your fingers to grip the material other than main strength and are almost impossible to get on. The only reasons it's standing up in the picture is that it's filled with something but in reality it's actually like trying to put on a deflated rubber balloon I wore these a week and threw them out in disgust.

title: DO NOT BUY FOR HIKING/BACKPACKING! Not tight enough, caused huge painful blisters.
text:
I never write Amazon reviews but felt obligated to share my experience. I bought these socks for a backpacking trip in Colorado for the 4th of July. Our group covered ~5 miles/day over three days with some regular elevation gain during the first two days. These socks were not snug enough and started giving me blisters on the back of my feet on the first day, after the first couple miles. I used my usual hiking boots that had not given me blisters with any other socks. I was stuck with these socks for the whole trip, which was very uncomfortable.

I almost posted photos of the blisters for effect but decided they were too graphic. One was the size of a nickel, one the size of two nickels. Same spot on both feet.

title: Super warm, comfortable socks - They lasted through only TWO wearings!
text:
These socks are incredibly comfortable. I'd say they're right up there with the best socks ever. Why only one star? They ripped completely across the toe seam after only two wearings! Do these socks have some kind of warranty? $17 a pair and they self-destruct after less than a few weeks.

FOLLOWUP: I contacted Wigwam socks directly and here is their reply: "Guruka, please accept our apologies. A replacement pair of socks will be sent. At times a stitch may be missed when the machine knits the toe closing which offers the most comfortable toe seam. Your order number is... Wishing you a safe and healthy holiday. Wigwam.com Customer Service"

So they do stand behind their product.

title: New balance model 608
text:
I've purchased New Balance products for decades.
But no more. I recently purchased model 608, after 3 months the sole at the tip of right shoe started to separate (see pics). I contacted New Balance customer service. I guess it's time to try Sketchers.

title: Were amazing past two years. They are thin and sloppy now?
text:
I loved this brand and these socks...I have ordered countless times for myself and friends and had these gifted to me and gifted to others.

The original socks I ordered were Tough, soft, thick enough to support steel toe boots but not too thick. They wore down on the back and heel area after solid use, and eventually turned so thin that they became uncomfortable, but that's after almost a year of hard work on my feet. With all that, Still 5 stars because I am tough on my socks and these ones have never let me dkw ...until my last orders

Ordered two packs for Christmas gifts, one for myself and one for a friend... His were mixed, I have not checked them out yet but my Navy ones were extremely flimsy and thin...loosely stitched. They are still decent socks, but not what I expected based on past orders. I usually dont do negative reviews...but it seems like the only way to get the response needed.

title: What a disappointment!
text: I had a pair of Wigwam socks for the last 10 years that I absolutely loved.  They finally got holes in them so I needed a new pair.  Obviously, being so happy with the last pair, I immediately searched for and purchased new Wigwam socks!  What a disappointment these new socks are compared to the old ones.  They don't fit well (way too tight around the calf, and too loose around the foot)(and I have size 13 wide feet), they're much thinner material than the old ones, and they constantly slip down (floppy toe every time you take your shoes off).  I wish I could've returned both pairs but I washed one to see if it got better.  Spoiler: it didn't.

title: Dramatic change in quality from these same socks I ordered 6 months ago
text:
I am very disappointed with my recent order and feel the quality has dropped dramatically. I have ordered these socks previously, back in June and love them. I have worn them everyday for 12+ hours at work in the woods and they are holding up great.

I decided to purchase some more and disappointed to find that the weight, thickness, and stitching has completely changed. Comparing them to the same socks are ordered 6 months ago the quality isn't even close. The socks I just ordered are not even close to medium weight, and feel more like Hanes crew socks. The logo and stitching is also different from the same socks I have previously ordered. I decided to give one pair a try today and ended up with blisters after 4 hours because how thin they are. I had to go back to the truck and put on the People's Socks I ordered 6 months ago. Night and Day difference.

What happened to the quality??? Maybe the picture will help. The sock on top is 6 months old and holding up great, the new sock is on the bottom.

When they arrived and I a squeezed a foot into one, I pulled it off to see if perhaps it wasn't really a "C/D" width.  Well, it was that, but I also saw the little tag stuck inside that said "uppers of man-made materials."  What the ???  My nose confirmed the fine smell of vinyl.  I went back to the Amazon description.  Indeed, the third bullet down reads "Lace-up sneaker in premium synthetic leather...."  The summary list is misleading, C/D ain't wide, and as a number of other reviewers have said, these shoes aren't what they used to be.  Back they go!

title: Dissapointed!
text:
Update 4/12/2017

The first 2 orders of socks I purchased were fantastic so I decided to order another. This last order of socks seemed like some cheap knockoff. The material was thin and the weaves were loose. It's like the company tried to outsource the product. I am so disappointed that I couldn't get what I paid for. I am returning this last order and will search for a better company. The sock on the left is the substandard sock and the sock on the right came from the first order.

-----

The material seems quality, the feel is very soft and nice. My girlfriend wears a size 5 shoe and I wear anything from an 8-9 mens and the socks fit us both comfortably. I received the small/medium green socks as a gift.

The socks do keep my feet warmer and my feet do not sweat. I don't have any feet issues, just wanted to try out these socks.

One thing I noticed is that the socks rub on my boots and cause some material buildup on the outside of the socks. I am hoping that this is just part of a break-in process. The socks are a little high priced, but they are quality socks.

text:

However, in this third purchase, one of the socks had a hole in the heel and a stitching issue in the toes right out of the box. I thought, no issue sence they have a 1 year warranty.
I sent an email to people socks to take advantage of their 1 year warranty and quickly got a response the next morning saying a replacement pair would be sent out the next Tuesday. Well...that was over a month ago. I have tried twice to email them about it and they will not respond to me. I am disappointed in their customer service.

I took my shoes off at the end of the day and the socks are very fuzzy and noticably thinner on bottom. I'm a big(read:fat) guy, but even so one day of sitting my my office shouldnt kill these socks.

title: Quality Eyewear!
text:
No compliments from others, but what matters is what I think - and I love them. So much I brought this second pair with green lenses. The first pair had gray lenses. I'll probably buy the brown lenses too. Being "Mil-Spec" and made in the U.S.A. are important to me, I didn't want an expensive pair made in China, as most folks are wearing today. Thanks to Amazon for offering AOs at a very affordable price.

Update: I should note the color of the green lenses are more of a gray-green, in fact I thought they were gray when I first put them on. Only comparing my gray pair to these could I see the difference.

Update 2: Bayonet temples, beneath the clear plastic ends caps of the metal bayonet temple arms show a lot of oxidation from sweat. Poor design - remove three stars from previous review. Also, lenses need to be polarized for outdoor use, these are not.

title: Quality is not as good as they used to be - what happened?

title: Wear out too quickly
text:
These are quite nice, a bargain for the price that I paid. I like these better than my more expensive merino blend socks (sw). Hopefully they will last just as long.

Another reviewer said that these socks are not very tight around the foot or leg, bulky around the ankle, and do not stay up on the calf. I did not find that to be the case. I wear size 11 shoes and have a slim/athletic build (normal-sized calves) and these fit me perfectly.

Update -

Since I was so pleased with my first order, I decided to order an additional 4 pairs. The quality on the second batch was not nearly as good as the first. All 4 pairs already have holes in the heel and ball of the foot. The first set of socks lasted several months, whereas this most recent batch were only good for about 6 weeks. I will say, they are great socks while they last.

title: you pay for "made in China"
text: So I've owned these boots for over a year, and they haven't held up all that well. I work with lumber and use these to ride my motorcycle. Within the first couple weeks, the rubber started peeling off the toe. Which is really the only complaint. The rubber under the toe begins to pull back and eventually rips off. Everything else about these boots are great. Sturdy, comfy and waterproof. I would probably not buy these again for my line of work, but I would get the super loggers. These ones were made in China.

title: Not the quality/service expected from Nuusol!  They don't warranty products for 6 months, as stated.
text:

This happened within a couple of months of having the sandals. I contacted Nuusol and they said they would not guarantee the sandals, because they were purchased through Amazon and not Nuusol.

Very disappointed, as other companies guarantee their products as long as you have a receipt and proof of purchase, (which I do). When I replied to the Nuusol Rep. after she told me they would not guarantee, noone ever replied to me again. Customer service?? Very Displeased with Nuusol since they claim to warranty their products agains poor workmanship and defects. They do not!

title: Lasted less than 6 months :(
text: I bought these for my husband in February based on great reviews. We live in a cool climate and he wears wool socks daily. He loved these socks! Within a few washes one pair had holes on each toe seam that were clearly a manufacturing defect. I set the pair aside to return them and forgot about them. Within a couple months I noticed that the ball of each remaining sock was wearing through. Now at the end of July every sock from my order either has a gaping hole or is threadbare. I'm pretty surprised! These were great while they lasted, but I really expected more out of them. Its back to Kirkland wool blend trail socks, which is a shame because these were so squishy and great when new, and I thought we'd found THE socks.

title: Short life of outer soul.
text:
I have purchased Wolverine work boots for the better part of 10 years. I have always gotten good life from the mens steel toe work boots.
Until I purchased this pair of composite toe boots. I purchased the end of August 2021. 1st- The boots were really tough for the first 30 days or more. This being the first pair of Wolverine boots that I can remember breaking in . 2nd- Here we are end of February 2022. The outer soul @ heal already FAILING. Along with the lacing towards the front of boot exterior. This is unacceptable for a 120$ pair of boots. I typically have gotten at least a year out of a pair of boots. Let me add, I service and install HVAC equipment. So itâ€™s not like The boots seeing sparks or heavy chemicals.
I am honestly disappointed with this pair of boots. So much so, I am thinking twice and three times before purchasing another pair. With the short life this pair of boots have experienced.

title: While these sunglasses are made of fine material, i
text:
While these sunglasses are made of fine material, i.e. plant based acetate, the fit and finish do not live up to the price. I was shocked to see that Allen Edmonds, at the time of this review, had a bunch of these glasses on clearance on their website for $89.99. The Sunglasses on sale at Allen Edomonds come with a leather case which you would have to pay extra for if you buy it directly from Capital Eyewear-. Never pay the full price for these glasses!!

Anyway, I bought two pairs of sunglasses from Capital Eyewear, at the full price, one from the Forrest and one from the Morgan series and both have issues. The sunglasses do not fit well largely due to the armsâ€™ length and the tightness of the space between them. The sunglasses were designed as unisex to fit men and women, however, if you have a relatively average size head it will not fit properly. One can check their website and you can see the sunglasses do not even fit some of the models adequately. You would have to wear them with the arms earpiece sticking above your ears. A lot of cheap sunglasses fit better!!

In addition, the finishing does not live up to any of the hype being hand-made and all. For instance, the edges are not smoothed out around the nose rest/pad so itâ€™s kind of sharp and not comfortable. The company brags about their 5-barrel wire core hinges and one pair had a washed barrel. One is better off with a pair of Persol or even Ray Ban and they even come with a two-year warranty as opposed to the 6 months warranty you get from Capital Eyewear.

title: Not the worst but no longer deserving of their old reputation.
text:
I've seen a lot of reviews that say the quality of this sock has gone down significantly and I believe them. They fit well and are comfortable but that's it. If you're walking around they keep your feet warm but sit still for about 15 minutes and you'll want to double layer. If you're hiking I feel like you might get away with wearing them twice without washing them. Maybe. After a month (during which I never put them in the dryer) three of them started to get tiny holes in them. Not from normal wear and tear, more like there were a few weak points in the yarn. I darned them and they held but I shouldn't have had to after so short a period. After 6 months they are all starting to wear thin in a couple places.

They're not terrible if you need winter socks on a budget but if you can spend the extra $15 - $20 on a better brand I definitely would.

title: This site is too vague about sizing and being a man/woman combined sizing.
text:
This web site for these socks is very confusing about sizing, as nowhere on the page does it say when you go to the size chart, that the 10-13 range is for women only. I had searched for Mens Nike socks when finding this particular option, and I have a 11 1/2 foot. When seeing a 10-13 range for a L size choice, that is what I picked, so my foot size would be in the middle of the range, not at the end and too tight.

When the socks arrived though, the package only indicated a 8-12 range, and nothing about any 10-13. Then I find out that 10-13 is a women range only, not a man. The 8-12, leaves my 11 1/2 foot in too tight a fit. Why do you not clarify the sizing for these socks, and what if a 13 or larger was needed?

title: Loved them dearly until the stupid ass adjustable nose pieces broke off.
text:
So as soon as i got these I fell in love with them because of how great they look and bc of the quality; they really do have a nice weighty feel to them and the lenses are thick.

Right from the start though I could tell those damn adjustable nose pieces were gonna be a problem... not to mention they're uncomfortable as hell and due to the weight of these glasses they're gonna push down on your nose very hard, leaving goofy marks on the side of your nose as a result.

They were the only part of the glasses that genuinely felt flimsy and low quality and sure enough a few months ago one of them outright snapped off, making the glasses basically unusable until I find a DIY way to fix them or rest on the nose comfortably. I feel kinda bad leaving 2 stars on these but man, I've gotten significantly more mileage out of the $12 sunglasses I got from urban outfitters (these glasses cost me almost 5 times that)

Lesson learned, stick with the cheaper brands. Somehow these $60 "american" made sunglasses don't even have polarization meanwhile half of the cheap <$15 chinese sunglasses you see on this site come polarized.

Meh. Big regret buying these for me personally, $60 down the god damn drain.

title: Not the quality/service expected from Nuusol!  They don't warranty products for 6 months, as stated.
text:
I have only used these indoors on a smooth floor surface. The rubber has become "very pliable" at the front and the front edge flips under causing me to stumble. This happened within a couple of months of having the sandals. I contacted Nuusol and they said they would not guarantee the sandals, because they were purchased through Amazon and not Nuusol.

Very disappointed, as other companies guarantee their products as long as you have a receipt and proof of purchase, (which I do). When I replied to the Nuusol Rep. after she told me they would not guarantee, noone ever replied to me again. Customer service?? Very Displeased with Nuusol since they claim to warranty their products agains poor workmanship and defects. They do not!

text:
I want to love these socks. I want to wear them every day. Problem is, I've been wearing them comfortably since I bought this 4 pack, wearing a pair almost every day. In two months time, I am already having to throw away a sock(with another one soon on its way to the trash), due to holes in the soles of the socks (do socks have soles?). For the price, I would have expected them to last a bit longer. I admit, I did put a lot of walking miles in this, and I really enjoy wearing these socks. Super comfortable and warm.

update- one month later and 6 of the 8 socks are useless and trash. That is absurd for the price...a crappy pair of hanes socks last longer.

title: Stretchy socks that are too small for size 13 feet
text: I can get my size 13 feet into these but the resulting elastic tension is uncomfortably tight.  The thickness of the sock when stretched this far also makes them just about as thin as regular socks.  Now the post by the guy wearing these in Arizona makes complete sense. I gave these to my wife who has size 7 1/2 (women's) feet. They came up to her mid-calf and the elastic tension was still enough to keep them contoured to her normal-width legs/feet.  She was happy to have the extra hiking socks.

title: Waist band roles up - aka: muffin tops all around.
text:
The build up was huge. Saw many online reviews and youtube videos promising that this is the best underwear to ever exist. Extremely disappointed to say - nope nope nope.

When I first put it own I thought "Ooo - they are on to something!"
Then, after putting my clothes on and wearing it for only several minutes I noticed the band roles up creating this huge waterfall of muffin tops. The panties are labeled as sizes 4-11 and I am a size 6-8 - so right at the midpoint. On paper, should be perfect..

In the butt, these are a little more comfortable than the VS thongs. The waist band is what's killing this for me.

title: Really wanted to like these socks...
text:
The socks just flat-out do not last. I bought 12 pairs (3 orders - 2 in 2016 and 1 in 2018) of them, and so many of them developed holes I am now left with about 6 pai... oh wait a minute, I just looked down at noticed another hole forming on the ball of my left foot. I guess that means I am down to 5 pairs.

I have had holes develop in the heel, ball, and toes, so it's not a case of me not trimming my toenails. Also, I do not wear these socks every day, as I have socks for other purposes (i.e. athletic for working out); during the Summer, I do not even wear socks.

I am going to be switching to another brand. Regardless of the positives (comfort, cost, made in USA), I cannot justify spending any more money on a faulty product.

title: Mediocre Sunglasses
text:
These supposed "military grade" aviator sunglasses do a poor job of protecting the eyes from the sun, regardless of what mm size you get: 52, 55, and 57 (I tried the 52 and 57 mm lenses before finally returning them to the store).

While for style purposes these aviators might be "cool" or hip, they do not function well. Perhaps you are inspired by watching the USA Network's show "Burn Notice" to look for a cheaper alternative to Oliver People's Victory 55/58, these are not a viable alternative.

The default lens (true color) is not polarized and it shows. Glare from the sun (especially when the sun is high in the sky) enters from the gap between your brow and the glass lenses, hurting the eyes.

The default lens is not dark enough for "normal" sunglass wearing conditions. You know, when it's sunny out?

These aviators also offer no form of wrap around protection from UV rays that enter from the sides of the face, so the damage to your eyes is a double wammy.

I can only assume polarized lenses would do far better in these sunglasses, but I didn't bother to try. The glasses themselves are already high priced considering what little protection they offer, so to get a polarized lens in them tacks on (at some stores) at least another twenty dollars.

The frames themselves are heavy but if you don't mind that you will appreciate the high quality metal ocnstruction. Ultimately, though, these aviators are based on a 60 year old design that is, while retro and cool, not what most folks are used to in a sunglass today.

Better to find a more modern aviator that offers a better fit on the face, a polarized lens and wrap around protection.

title: Size changed - much too big
text:
I've been buying these socks on subscription for maybe 3 years now? They've always been fine, not exceptional, but they fit, have good cushion and stretch, and last a decently long time.

The ones I got this time are about an inch and a half longer than the last batch (see picture). I was able to do a fair comparison because I still had the last package unworn and unwashed. The new ones have the same label - women's, one size fits most - but they're closer to the standard size for men's socks than women's.

I buy women's socks because I'm a men's 7 (women's 8.5-9ish?) in shoes, so these are not going to work for me, and I'm pretty sure they won't work for most women.

title: Agree with other reviewers, different countries = different sizing
text: I bought one of these shirts over a year ago and absolutely loved it, nice fit throughout the body, neck hole isn't all stretched out, and the tall size adds 2 inches for my 6'4" frame. That said, I ordered 3 more towards the end of last year, 2 in heather grey, 1 in carbon grey.  When I started to wear the carbon grey, it felt looser, and the neck wasn't a great fit (noticeable on zoom calls).  I assumed it was due to the fact it was a different material so I bought only heather grey and have good luck; until today.  I ordered one more shirt to get ready to go on a trip and noticed the tag was different in the neck and it said "loose fit"...of which there is no way to see or choose this on Amazon.  This thing fits like a parachute in the same  large tall size and the neck hole is gigantic.  Needless to say I am returning it, but now I don't know what to do other than order and rotate them through Kohls return until I get one made properly.  How can Carhartt have the same "K87" shirt, made in two different places be sold with this much of a delta?

title: More than one size "one size"....wrong size
text:
Warning. One sizes is not one size!! My wife really likes these over prices underwear. So for mothers day I thought I would get her some. Wanting to make sure I got the correct size I looked at a pair she already has. It says "one size". So I ordered the size "one size".
She just opened them and they are not the same size as the ones she also has that say "one size" they are a different size. Come to find out they are a different size "one size". What the heck is that all about. There are two...or more "one size"
So thank you Hanky Panky for making something as easy as matching sizes impossible.
Needless to say the mothers day gift was a bust. Because I got the wrong "one size".
Next time I will stick to a brand that actually has standard sizes.

title: Too bad they changed them somewhere along the way.
text:
A ghost of what was. Jan 11 2016 update.

I wore these socks daily for three years, and loved them until the ball of the socks started to wear out. So I looked them up using my previous orders and ordered some more. Somewhere along the way the socks were drastically changed, they are now very, very thin. These are more sports socks now rather than keep your feet warm socks.

Yes I know these are just socks, but when you find something that meets every expectation you have, and then it is changed for the worse, it is disappointing.

So now I'm off to find a replacement since my feet are cold, and will stay that way if I were to use these socks.

These are some very nice socks, okay they are just socks so not something that will rock your world but they are exactly what I was looking for. Nice and warm, came through the wash with no appreciable shrinking and they are very soft. I'm ordering my second set today. I do wish they were taller, I'm 6-4 so they really don't come up to the top of my combat boots, but they are great for what they are.

1 Year later.
Socks are still fantastic! My everyday socks during the winter and they feel great everyday I put them on. Warm, comfortable, and still in great shape after I've worm them every day last winter and this one. They have stood up to the regular wash and wear cycle like a champ. I'm not sure what else I can say about how great these socks are, but if you give them a chance i'm pretty darn sure you will love them as much as I do.

Nice and warm, came through the wash with no appreciable shrinking and they are very soft. I'm ordering my second set today. I do wish they were taller, I'm 6-4 so they really don't come up to the top of my combat boots, but they are great for what they are.

1 Year later.
Socks are still fantastic! My everyday socks during the winter and they feel great everyday I put them on. Warm, comfortable, and still in great shape after I've worm them every day last winter and this one. They have stood up to the regular wash and wear cycle like a champ. I'm not sure what else I can say about how great these socks are, but if you give them a chance i'm pretty darn sure you will love them as much as I do.

title: Amazing, simply Amazing....at first...
text:
This shirt is a godsend. I have had excessive sweat under my arms since I was 11. I always wore strong anti-perspirants and would still sweat. I would take multiple showers and still sweat. I found Certain Dri and started using that. That has definitely lessened my sweat but not fully. I even combine that with Degree and Mitchum, that is how bad I have sweat. I am a big dude, 6'0 278 lbs, muscular husky and ordered the XXL. It fits fine though the neck is a little wide. However, I have full coverage under my arms and I LOVE IT. Yesterday was the first day in 25 years my dress shirt did not show sweat. If I tell you how happy I was you would not even believe me. Picture this gym rat guido on the verge of tears last night for how happy I was to actually show my mom I had no sweat under my arms after work. I just ordered 2 more as the price is not cheap but will eventually have a lot of these in my dressers. You will feel wetness at times under your arm pits but nothing soaks through. It dries quick and no smell. I never had a deodorant problem, just a sweating problem, but the pad itself still keeps fresh all day. I recommend buying a size up to get more coverage. It is an undershirt, not made to wear as a regular shirt, does exactly as it says. I honestly can't wait to try light colored shirts again.

***EDIT as of 5/1/17 - washed the shirt and it actually got tighter and it makes the pad cover less area. Also noticed a little dampness seep through to my button down. Little disappointed. I did not sweat more today than when I first wore it. Granted, it soaked up most of the sweat but still not ALL of it.

***2nd EDIT as of 5/15/17 - wore the shirt for mother's day, doesn't seem to have shrunk more BUT i sweated through the pads at the top and bottom, not in the middle - now very disappointed

title: Dramatically Thinner than they Used to Be
text:
I bought several packs of these in mid-2015 and rated them 5 stars. They were thick and warm.

Fast forward to December 2016. The price has been increased by $5 and the socks are now about half as thick as they previously were. People Socks is coasting on the five-star ratings for their previous product while replacing it with a cheaper, less durable one.

Two stars. It's still a fine sock for moderately cool weather. But they should have listed it as a new product, rather than deceptively swapping it for the old one.

title: At first they are warm and comfortable. Soon after they begin to get noticeable wear ...
text:
These socks are disappointing. At first they are warm and comfortable. Soon after they begin to get noticeable wear on the heel and ball areas of my foot, they are not as comfortable when those areas get thin, and not nearly as warm. How soon? I checked and have ordered 12 pairs of the long socks, and 16 pairs of the quarter length, since November of 2015 (one calendar year). I actually came on to order more pairs after realizing my current stock are getting holes in them again, my wife mentioned I go through them too fast so I checked my order history. For what it is worth, I am fairly active and sometimes wear one pair over the other.

I love these socks as they fit great, don't fall down, are warm etc. But I can't recommend them, I wonder why they have so many great reviews with a few like mine scattered throughout? Maybe I have "abrasive" feet? Sadly i'm off to find another brand.

Update a few months later: I tried a few other brands, even the high dollar Darn Tough socks. I am back, and ordering another year supply I figure 16 pairs ought to do it...

Another thing worth mentioning, I didn't realize before but these PS socks stay up on my calfs (I'm fit, I feel my calfs are larger than the average guy) better than any of the other brands I tried, I was not aware how annoying it is to pull my socks up all the time until I tried other brands.

title: Well made, aesthetically pleasing, very uncomfortable (unfortunately)
text: I got them and I put them on and they felt pretty good. They come with a passable foam insole I thought would be adequate. after wearing them for a while and trying 3 different insoles I gave up and sent them back. No matter what I tried after an hour or so on my feet I felt like I was standing on granite and after a few more hours my feet, back, and legs would be in pain or at the very least sore. I couldn't clock out and get to my car fast enough to take a load off.  One specific point of discomfort is where the boot flexes as you walk near the first row of eyelets. As I walked the boot dug into the top of my right foot (with all the insoles). It really disappoints me because these are extremely well made and great looking boots.

title: Don't do it!
text: I'm writing this review honestly because I want you to know what you're getting yourself into if you buy these shoes. I've had these shoes for 2 years, so I can tell you all about them. I looooooove the design and color and fit. But they are nasty. Firstly, the material is super cheap, you can tell by how lightweight the shoe is. Secondly, there is nilch ventilation, and so your feet get sweaty and smelly. Usually this happens 4+ hours, less in hot weather. And, if you get them wet, (like all shoes they take a bit to dry) the lining inside the shoe or whatev is breeding ground for mildew. Even though I wash them, they smell so so so nasty. They've given me multiple foot fungi. To top it off, they're called "running" shoes, but I discovered that they were giving me shin splints and that is just wrong (they don't have any sort of arch support). If I had more money, I would have replaced these shoes a long time ago.

title: Not Impressed. Few design flaws and gimmicky features.
text:
So I thought since these were thick rubber, looked good, made in the USA, etc, these would be worth the money.

To the touch, they feel nice. I was impressed first unboxing them, but then I realized something kind of gimmicky about them. The rubber is designed to look like it has a thick sole. On the exterior, you can see the line where a thick sole would normally start, but once you slide your feet in, they slide right past this border and you realize it's just a superficial exterior line that has nothing to do with the thickness of the sole. I don't see how these would hold up really well to construction needs when you're stepping on sharp pieces of wood, nails, other junk, etc...

Then I noticed there were huge lumps of rubber on the inside sole of one overboot. When I flipped it inside out, it looked like it was leftover from the injection molding they did to create the boot, but you could definitely feel it very obviously through my boot. This wasn't a huge issue as I could slice it off with a razor blade, so I did that so that they were flat. I hadn't decided against these yet, but then what happened next was a complete deal-breaker.

As I had them on and they were finally comfortable and I started walking around, I noticed that my heels started to slide upwards in the overboot, so that there was a space opening up underneath my heel and scuffing on the floor as I walked. The reason I believe is that the sole footprint size actually tapers inward a bit, so that the heel sole of your actual boot wants to settle somewhere about an inch above the sole of the overboot. This should not happen as I wear 10.5 size shoes and these are the correct size L overboot. Walking around with the heels always dragging on the ground because of a space between the heel of my boot and the heel of the overboot would definitely result in a worn out spot on the heel and they would not last long at all. It at least wasn't worth over $50 to find out. So I'm returning these and back to the drawing board. I wanted to like them, but they actually just look way more durable and practical than they really are.

title: Low weight and fragile
text:
Bought these boots in May 2022, and the sole of the right boot was broken by the end of June 2022.
The boots are incredibly light, the lightest I've even worn. The amount of protection they offer for the weight isn't bad but I'd have preferred a tougher, heavier boot.

The composite toe doesn't offer much in the way of protection, nor do the 'armored' side sections. Maybe I just got unlucky and got a set with a defective boot-sole, but I doubt it and I'd rather go with a heavier more protective boot.

title: Made well. Design? Not so much.
text:
So I'm a big fan of wool socks the year 'round. About a year ago I purchased People Socks wool socks for boots. Those socks came to just below the knee and are awesome. As a result I purchased these "crew" socks which I am less enthusiastic about.

Like the boot socks I mentioned previously these seem to be well made. I am a size 10 shoe and purchased the Large version of this sock which is stated to fit sizes 9-11. The design is flawed in my opinion. This sock rides higher (about 2" higher) than a traditional crew sock. As a result the top of the elastic area seems to go as far as the widest part of my calf - as a result the socks slide down and gather around my ankles. If they were a little shorter it is my belief they would stay up, essentially clinging to my upper ankle and lower calf area like a truer crew fit. My wigwam, smart wool and REI wools socks seem to have a similar fit to each other.

I am disappointed in these socks.

text: Originally they were set to arrive on Thursday, then it changed to Sunday. When they finally got here, the wood was dinged/dented and the metal bar connecting the heel & toe was scratched up. Also, on the underside of the trees it was chipped, with small chunks missing; looks as though they've been used. Now in contrast, I ordered a pair of Stratton shoe trees at the same time (which arrived 3 days earlier). And when they arrived they were smooth all over, wrapped in tissue paper inside the box AND had a great strong cedar smell... everything these did not have! title: Not the same as the old AE shoe trees...
text: Two years ago I bought 2 pairs of these AE Shoe Trees from Zappos and love them. The craftsmanship was spot on, the cedar smell was strong and the sizing was perfect. I still use them regularly. Recently I bought a new pair of shoes and decided to buy a new set of shoe trees, this time from Amazon, not Zappos. What a disappointment. First of all, the cedar wood feels cheap. The old wood was robust and thick, the new ones are just flimsy and thin. The cedar smell is mild at best, where the smell on the old ones is still nice and strong. Even worst, the fit is smaller! I can't believe AE let a simple product like their shoe trees go to waste! Never buying another pair of shoe trees from AE!

title: way too small
text:
I usually wear a 14 D but have a pair of Allen Edmunds brogue derby (Leeds? I bought them secondhand) that are 13 E and fit nicely. I bought the XL trees, expecting that there would be at least 1/4 inch of compression on the heel of the tree. There's nearly 3/8 inch of gap between the heel of the tree and the backstay. The box does indicate these are XL for sizes 12-14, but I would be surprised if they were snug in size 12s. If I seat the expanding section as deep into the toe as it will go they're probably better than not having anything.

The two stars are for aesthetics and the quality of the cedar.

title: Inferior to Champion shorts from a few years ago
text: Compared to Champion's mesh short from a few years ago, these are more lightweight, but feel much more flimsy.  The pockets are too narrow to be of any real use for anything more than a small keyring and a wallet (even a thin one) is out of the question.  They have no heft so you feel as though you are wearing nothing and are made of a very thin dry-fit material that seems very easy to tear at the seams, like the bottom of the pocket entry cut.  Some people might see these things as an improvement, but I do not.

title: Now thinner, wear out fast, I do not recommend
text:
When they first arrived they were great, and they are great socks out of the box. Warm, but breathable so your feet won't sweat. I love merino wool socks, I own a few brands, People included. However, these are not the same socks People sold even last year. These are thinner and mine are all wearing out after just a few months of use. Thinning on the bottom, holes in the heal. Of the original 8 socks, I have three left that do not have holes in them. I just wear them around the house, nothing extreme, and not all the time. Dollar store socks last about this long. I am frustrated and still can't believe how cheap these have become.

There are a few brands that make good merino wool socks, I would look elsewhere. I cannot recommend these less.

title: Severe drop in quality. Insulting.
text:
These used to be my favorite sock. I immediately threw out my entire sock drawer after discovering the brand, and refilled it with nothing but multiple packs of this sock. About once a year some would finally wear out and Iâ€™d get one new package to replace them. And life was good.

But the most recent package revealed a severe drop in quality. The wool content is obviously much reduced; formerly tight and fitting socks are loose and too stretchy, even when put in a dryer. And two of the socks started splitting between the toes after a single wearing.

The overall design of the socks seems to be fundamentally different, so I donâ€™t think this is a matter of a single faulty package. I worry theyâ€™ve made serious changes to cut costs, but Iâ€™m afraid it will cut their customer numbers. Theyâ€™ve lost me, at least.

Edit: After 10 months of use, the sets of socks I bought when I first wrote this review have utterly fallen apart or become so irreversibly stretched out that they're worthless and I've thrown them all away. Meanwhile, the original version of People Socks that I bought 4+ years ago are still going strong. What happened to this product?! I'm so upset at what I view as a betrayal and scam on their customer base that I've removed yet another star. I would have much preferred that they doubled the price of these socks than have reduced the quality as they did. Shame!

title: Didn't last and no response to warranty claim
text:
UPDATE BELOW ORIGINAL REVIEW
[[ASIN:B01DX6PT6W Brown Small-Medium 4pairs 71% Premium Merino Wool Crew Hiking Socks Made in USA People Socks]]

They seemed OK for a couple of months and then they started wearing out. It seems like a lot of people are having the same problem. They are supposed to have a one year warranty but I have not gotten a response back from the company after multiple attempts to contact them and providing photos, order number, etc. I might go with the more expensive Darn Tough next time...

After reaching out via email a couple of times, then Facebook, then leaving this review I was contacted and sent replacement socks. They said that Amazon orders do not normally qualify for their one year warranty. These are supposed to be a more durable. I will update after a time and see.

title: These are good socks for the price
text:
These are good socks for the price, but didn't last as long as I expected. Mine wore out much quicker than the more expensive but comparable thickness Smartwool socks that I own. While you get four pairs of People's Socks for the same price as one pair of Smartwools, I wore the bottoms out in all four pairs after around 6 months of once a week use. The comparable Smartwool socks are still kicking after a few years.
That said, the fit and comfort of these socks are great. Just wish they would last longer.

title: Nice looking boots, poor quality
text:
The Good:
I really like the styling of these boots, they were exactly what I've been shopping around for. They're also pretty comfortable for a new pair of boots.

The Bad:
After owning them for only one month and having worn them less than 10 times, they are already showing quality/durability issues. On both boots, the stitching that holds together the sole and welt together is failing, causing these layers to come apart. Only a month in and they had to be taken to a cobbler, making them perhaps the worst quality shoes I've ever bought. The cobbler will restitch them, then add an additional protective sole layer to protect the stitching and keep them from failing again.

Take away:
After the repairs, hopefully I'll be enjoying these boots for years to come. I will not however, be buying Thursday Boots again.

title: No more American shoe sizes?
text:
What's up? It seems that our wide foot sizes are no longer being made in that these shoes were made in an Asian nation, not recalling just which one right now. Hence, my size B width is no longer available. I know I can get around this by ordering a longer shoe but who wants to have large-looking feet? I tried at the department store, too, and they only make N (narrow) and M (medium) widths in these shoes. The M is not as wide as the B width I had always used. And, what about the formerly available C, D widths?

I am very disappointed because I love this style. My hope now is that with wearing them I can go through the painful stretching process and make them work. Otherwise, I'll have to abandon this style and shop elsewhere.

title: How the mightly has fallen.
text:
The pair of Chippewa boots that I received today were made in China, and parts that were leather on my old pair are now either vinyl or padded cloth. My older pair were made in the USA.

This new leather boot is much stiffer and unforgiving for the foot because of the man made vinyl and padded cloth materials on the inside of the boot, and I don't see how you can "break" them in, as you would do if the interior of the boot was leather.

I don't care much for the soft "rubber" trim at the top of the boot either. This is a wear point for many of my work boots, and this part will split, wear out and fall apart quickly. The reinforced leather trim on my "made in USA pair" split after many years of heavy use, but never wore out. I would have the old boots repaired by Chippewa, but at a cost of $90.00, plus the cost of shipping both ways, it really isn't worth it.

These new Chippewa boots are also not true as to size. I ordered a 12 medium and this pair I received is more like a 13 E (wide) even though the size printed on the inside of the tongue does say 12 M. I had to slip on a double pair of hikers socks for the boot to fit.

No more "mail order" for me on shoes or boots, since it seems that many brands presently being made have manufacturing mistakes that can only be seen in person.

title: Lasted 4 winters
text: These socks were great while they lasted. I bought them in 2015 and they lasted about 4 winters. I finally had to start throwing them away this winter because the heel and ball of the foot are so worn through that I can feel the cold tile through them. While 4 winters may seem like a long time, I have a pair of Wigwam socks (that I have worn every winter and on multiple hiking trips throughout each year) that I bought in 2008 and are still in good shape. I would not purchase again.

title: Soft and comfy. Also pricey. And snagging/pilling already...
text:
Update: I am adjusting my rating to two stars for this top. After wearing only twice, it has stated pilling on the arms and has several small snags. Given the price, I would expect more. I did not wash it with anything that would have snagged it and have not worn it for anything but office work. I am negatively impressed. VERY poor performance/durability.

Original: I needed a basic navy blue long-sleeved shirt and this one came up on Vine as an option. I have to say that, had I seen the price and not gotten it for free to review, I would not consider this item. $124 for a knit shirt that looks like a fancy t-shirt is not within my tolerance level. I don't pay much attention to brands so I don't know if it is the name that contributes to the hight cost.

That said, the shirt is very nice. The fabric is soft and it is well constructed. They claim that it has a shelf bra for going braless, which it does. But don't expect any support from that. Also, the fabric would do nothing to cover nipple outlines so, if that would bother you, you would need to wear a bra with this shirt.

I think I will wear this shirt often, because it is comfortable and versatile. But I think I could find an equally versatile and comfortable shirt for about $30. I will give it 4 stars, which does not address the price. If I were to address the listed price, I would give it 3 stars. Just not worth the asking price.

The price is very attractive, but I've had more expensive socks last for years, while I don't expect these to last more than a few months.

Additionally, I have found these a little too large for my size 10.5 feet. There is a fair amount of material left bunched up at the heel, which I'm sure isn't helping with the wear issues.

title: Not the best, not the worst.  Well made for the price.
text:
Good price, decent boot. I like the eyelet construction, using washers on the interior side. They are fairly light compared to some of my other boots, and there's really nothing overtly wrong with them. But the sole feels like it's going wear down pretty quickly (which does however make them a little more shock absorbent I think) and the shank/midsole portion of the boot is a little weak. I wouldn't want to be on a round-rung ladder for too many hours with these.

The fit is right on size, and there was really no break in discomfort. Of course they felt better after a few dozen days of wearing them, that's how leather boots work, but they weren't bad straight out of the box.

Hooray for oblique toe though! I wish more manufacturers would make them this shape.

title: A little pricey for what you actually get.
text: I was really excited to receive this T shirt but I think my expectations were a bit too high because I was dissapointed. The concept is great! However for almost $30 its just a cotton T shirt with padding built into the pits. The padding itself is a bit bulky and noisy - when you move around you can hear a crinkling noise under your arm. My other disappointment was the lengh, it's barely long enough to tuck in but may come untucked on movement. I still gave 3 stars because again I love the concept but I personally feel like a little better quality material needs to be used, they need added length so you can tuck and also the padding may need to be modified somehow so its not so bulky and noisy.

title: My feet feel claustrophobic..... and hot.
text:
Early impressions:
It's a good shoe, but the width is definitely too small. Picked up a 3E and, while it needs some working in, the ball if my foot runs just a tad bit over the sole and hugs the wall. I can't even imagine awful a standard width must feel. Also, this shoe gets hot. My last pair was also totally waterproofed and the works, but it feels like it's half the heat. I imagine it's heavily due to the lack of foot room.

Consider buying a size of .5 - 1 bigger and don't forget to check off for wide option. I might just return them and go for something else.

title: dont know how to explain this
text: The shoes are good enough. I got a slightly larger size because my feet are an in between size and I would likely be wearing these with thick sox so got a size larger. A bit wide in the heel, but that is just the shape of my foot--narrow heel. I got these to slip into before going out to the chicken house or walking the dog while the ground is still wet. I find it even with the wide heel to not easily slip in and out of them. That is not a fault with the shoe, I suppose--just the way they are made. But look at the pic. I was traveling and had them in a plastic bag in a paper bag (I had washed them off before packing so put them in a plastic bag) and had them in the back seat of my car. One of the black shoes turned blue! I got black in case I wanted to wear them as street shoes when it rains--guess I will just be wearing them to the chicken house now.

title: Disappointed!! After all the supplier's hype about cutting ...
text:
Disappointed !!
After all the supplier's hype about cutting out the middle-man and maintaining quality, I expected more. I wore the socks for 5 hours, most of the time sitting not walking. I wore them with properly fitted shoes. The wool is already shedding in chunks and the color has changed from light blue to almost white at the heel where they have worn away. I assume that the old adage : 'you get what you pay for ' is again applicable. (not that $6 a pair is that inexpensive, with no middle-man's fees to account for). I will buy my merino socks elsewhere from now on; 'People Socks' suck.

title: Expected more based on price and reviews..
text:
I had previously gone cheap on hiking socks and that didn't go too well for me. When I saw the amount of positive reviews for these I figured I should bite the bullet and pay the 30 dollars for 4 pairs of quality socks. To my surprise, the first time I washed them after using (I waited to wash all 8), I found 2 of the socks already showing signs of falling apart.

They were all washed in warm water, inside out, and not machine dried - as instructed on the package. If I'm already seeing this after 1 wash (1 week of ownership), I'm not very confident these are going to be around all summer as I had hoped they would be..

Overall, I'm not pleased and will be buying a different brand going forward.

title: which is a bit of a pain but the worst part was the smell
text: I bought these socks for work, from a comfort angle and not a keep my feet warm angle. That said, these socks are medium thick and I'm sure would do well to keep your feet warm. They can't be dried normally, and the manufacturer recommends turning them inside-out for washing, which is a bit of a pain but the worst part was the smell. There was a strong wet dog kind of smell to them after the first wash. Once dry the smell was drastically reduced and as they have been worn and washed the smell has gone away.

title: Not bad. Only time will tell.
text:
The price is certainly right, but I agree with the other reviewers who said that these socks begin to wear noticeably almost immediately. They haven't worn through after a couple wears and washings, but I can see areas that sit against the friction points of my feet(balls of feet, ankles etc) that are wearing more than the rest of the sock. I'll have to wait and see how well they hold up to the test of time.

All this being said, the socks are warm and fairly thick. I would say somewhere between medium and heavy thickness. They are listed as fitting size 12 and I would say that's accurate since they are a little small on my size 13/14 feet.

Unless you are willing/able to spend a lot more money for a higher grade wool sock these should last you a couple winters.

title: Great protection needs some continued work
text: I just received this product a few days ago and I was sort of shocked by the thickness of the armpit pads.  Also the protected area makes rubbing noise.  I enjoyed being able to go to a seminar without worry, no issues, my outer shirt was dry but the shirt itself was very wet feeling against my armpit.  I was pretty sweaty that day so I was impressed with how it kept my dress shirt dry but not so happy about how moist, cool, and heavy from saturation it was.  It is a good product but I would like to see the pad lines diminished so they are not so obvious, less rubbing noise, and that the barrier would feel dry and not so moist against the skin when saturated by hyperhidrosis armpits.  Looking to try another brand unless they can create something more like Sutran products (which are unfortunately very pricey especially the shipping.

title: Change in sole from previous shoes
text: I loved the first pair of 608 V5 I had. They looked great and wore very well. The last pair I got looked identical: same materials, same pattern, same pattern on the sole. However, the sole on the second pair is about 3/8" more narrow in the ball of the foot which makes the shoe look and feel much different. I called New Balance and they could not tell me they were aware that they were making two different versions of what is supposed to be the same model shoe. I am very dissappointed because I really wanted the same shoe I had but this last shoe (bought both at Amazon) is simply not the same shoe.

title: I have been through some expensive brands and my favorite are still Darn tough merino wool socks
text: Ok, My honest review.. I use merino socks (ALOT) solely for hiking/backpacking/mountaineering/etc. I have been through some expensive brands and my favorite are still Darn tough merino wool socks. The "People socks" tend to slip around and aren't quite a snug fit for hiking purposes(will eventually cause blistering if used for backpacking). However, they are much cheaper and the same type of product. You do get what you pay for and they are a great deal for everyday use. When using these on a 12 mile hike last weekend with a 30lb pack, my feet were slipping around in the sock just enough to rub blisters in the strangest places. On the same hike, using the same boots but the darn tough brand, had no problems. It may not be a big deal to some.. Just my 2 cents. The darn tough socks keep their form even after wearing all day,wash, repeat.. the people socks have not but once again, a great value for normal everyday use.

title: Not breathable
text: my pair arrived and I wore them around the house for a week with a pair of dress socks under regular work socks to break the shoes in. I, during the first week noticed so much heel slippage I had to try tying the laces in different way to alleviate the issue which only lead to shoes being to tight above my toes. i had found during wearing the boots during my work day that they are not breathable,  I work in Air conditioning in Attics as my trade where breathability helps a lot. The soles on tile surfaces have no traction if the tile is even slightly wet. After 2 months of wearing the boots every day to work, I have set them aside as back up boots due to the discomfort I feel from wearing these boot all day. While I completely expect the boots to hold up I do not continue to wear them for work as often as I had expected.

On the other hand, these are the PERFECT socks for around the house. Incredibly soft, like little sweaters for your feet. I stopped wearing slippers because these are so much more comfortable. Breathable and don't smell bad no matter how long I wear them.

title: Very comfortable, warm wool socks
text: These are great socks, I really like them.  They're comfy, warm, and suited to cold temperatures.  They aren't as thick as I would like them so they fill out my winter boots.  And after wearing them for a few seasons they've definitely worn through in the high friction areas (heel, toes, soles).  The first year or two these were my favorite socks, not they're the last socks in the drawer I wear before laundry.  Again, not saying they're a bad sock, they're very soft and comfortable.  But they've worn out faster than my other wool winter socks and I probably won't be rebuying them.  Made in the USA from quality material, but they don't hold up to the amount of use I need.

title: Meh...
text: I know these are 70 or 71% but if you've ever worn 100% wool socks, you can really feel the difference. These don't insulate as well as 100%, also after a single wash they do shrink some and they've gotten tighter on my feet- putting them on isn't exactly easy right out of the wash. These are good beaters for hiking and all, but if you're looking for ultimate warmth, go 100%. These are definitely better than cotton or acrylic or polyester for heat retention.

title: Started out great, Holes showed up after 6 months
text:
When i first bought these around Christmas time they were fantastic. They felt great, excellent cushioning, and my feet never got too cold nor too warm. I was so impressed, I bought multiple sets over a few months so that they would hopefully not wear out as fast.

However i noticed after 6-7 months or so, most of them have a dark spot on the bottom, and these spots are actually holes where the wool has completely worn out. I have always washed them gently with cold water, and never threw them in the dryer. I am on my feet most of the day, for most days of the week, however I felt like these should have been able to stand up for a while longer.

text: I've been wearing New Balance shoes nearly 30 years. This pair took a while to break in, but even so, they still are not as comfortable as the many pairs I have owned before and my feet start to hurt after 6-7 hours. It is disappointing to me that the quality I used to expect seems to have fallen off. I need solid soled shoes, not waffle patterned based, due to foot issues. I'm going to have to think about shifting to another brand as my regular use shoe if I continue to run into such problems. Disappointing to be sure.

title: Although a nice fit and thickness, the quality isn't quite up to Military issue specs.
text:
These are almost identical in thickness, texture, and fit to military issue glove lines. Differences are:
These gloves have both a nice fit and thickness to hem. They are indeed "cold weather" liners, meant to be used inside leather shells with a strap across the wrist to cinch the leather.

As noted by another reviewer, however, these are 70% wool and 30% nylon.

As also noted by another reviewer, there is also loose yarn at the V in between the bottom of the fingers. I turned these gloves inside-out and found loose yarn ends in between the base of the fingers that aren't tied off properly. Using a knitting needle and find tweezers, I'll tie these off before using.them.

I've owned a half-dozen pair of glove liners are/were standard Army issue (after 20 years of use, though, they've all give up the ghost). All of my military issue gloves were 100% wool and there was never a loose yarn or unraveling problem.

Amazon sells 100% wool military glove liners for about the same price. I'll try some of those next and update this review when I can compare this with another glove that I have in hand.

title: No way these fit feet below 9 or 10
text: They are not very tight around the foot or leg.  My shoe size is 10.5 and I am a biker with muscular calves but I don't have tree-trunk calves.  They probably fit a size 12 very well, but they are bulky around the ankle and do not stay up the calf on me.  You need to have tree trunk calves in order to make these socks work ideally.  Even then, there's still probably going to be an issue in the ankle if you're size is much less than 10 or 9.  That said, they are warm and do seem to be durable.  They're just not the best all-around hiker socks I have had.  I probably won't buy them again.  I guess I should have purchased the 2-pack instead of the 4-pack.

The tread pattern seems deliberately designed to pick up every stone and piece of dirt out there. Whatever happened to quality and common sense?

title: Used to be a good value, don't hold up IMO
text:
These now cost 35% more than when I first started purchasing in 2016. Inflation, I get it, but $10 per pair is steep for the characteristic poor longevity. These are my favorite winter sock, warm, dry fast, comfortable all day. The problem is they don't last long unless maybe you hand wash, but they are socks after all, no one is about to do that... So they end up lasting 2 years for me before holes form. I have about 12-15 pairs in rotation at any given moment, so they get worn maybe 15 times a year during the coldest days. Thats just 30 wears/washes before they need to be retired. That's not great.

So I came back to order more and I see the price increase is extreme and the product quality looks exactly the same. I've tried other variants of their socks and they too have the sort lifespan issue. Ever single one. Less wool, same ~30 wear life, it's practically part of the brand. At this point I'm not sure I want to keep going with People Socks since the value just isn't there any more.

title: OK, but too big for my size 10-11 feet
text:
Beware the six 5-star reviews appearing on November 8th!! They are the typical one or two word reviews from people who have only one or two reviews to their names. These are the reviews you pay a few bucks for to juice your product.

Now, I have been wearing these socks for a few weeks now. They are not as thick as the old Kirkland ones that are my favorites. The Kirkland ones from the past couple of years are terrible now - thin, too small, and wear out quickly. So, I searched far and wide to find my winter replacements. I settled on these. The quality seems good but they are a little thin for me and do not keep my toes warm as well as I would like. My main gripe (and the three stars) is that they are too large. I wear a size 10 - 10.5 street shoe, and a 11.5 running shoe. When I pull them on, the heel stretches up towards the Achilles. If I place the sock heel over my heel, the excess material bunches up under my arch. There is apparently only one size for these in men's. So, if you have large feet, these will probably be fine for you. Otherwise, take care with the sizes.

title: Good Price - Not Quite Right
text:
I'm a smartwool fan, but after too many short-lived, grossly overpriced pairs, I was ready for an alternative. It's hard to find 70% merino in a sock. Even when they're called merino, it's often like 20% or less. I was excited to try these, and I'm not totally disappointed, but several things dampen my enthusiasm. First, the sock construction and sizing is odd. There's extra elastic through the mid-foot (the so-called arch support) but the toe box is large and (for a men's size 11) the large male sock is just too bulky and doesn't fit snugly to my foot. Second, the material is shiny, suggesting that the synthetic component is a bit more prominent than might be expected. Compared to the name brand merino socks I own, it just doesn't stack up in material quality or build, but then i suppose, as always, you get what you pay for.

Recommended with reservations.

title: Nice looking and okay for general use
text:
I'm disappointed in these shoes. Definitely not representative of my other experiences with New Balance shoes. I bought these after reading online reviews. I normally buy standard width. When I put these on they were way too tight. I tied having them stretched and that did not fix the fit. I ordered a new pair and selected wide, that did the trick. They fit comfortably and I took a short walk in them, a mile on a mostly flat area. They did fine, but I could feel a bit of rubbing and as the leather relaxes with age it's going to cause calluses if I do several miles in them.
I've relegated them to weekend duty. They are fine for causal used but I can't recommend you use them for real exercise.

title: Fabric description confusion
text:
The dress I received seems to be authentic however it is different from the fabric on the sleeveless version that I also ordered. The tag shows 63% polyamide 33% viscose 4% elastane which is the same fabric description listed at top of the description for this dress, but there is another fabric description at the bottom which is different.

The fabric on sleeveless version is better than this one. This one arrived wrinkled from packing did not hang out even after a number of days whereas the sleeveless version was folded the same way but not wrinkles. So I am returning this one.

I love the version with sleeves but I am going to try to find it in the fabric of the sleeveless version (which incidentally is the same fabric as what is listed on the bottom of the product description).

title: bought these for a friend
text:
My friend usely wears an 8 1/2 M, she got a 9M ..fits fine for her. She loves the color red. the tightness in the ball part of the shoe will stretch she figures. She didn't mind that the shoe is synthetic tops..what's the difference she says. I tried to explain the difference between the glove soft leather that princess shoes were known for and this synthetic feel and look. She didn't care..she has worn princess style reeboks since the late 80's so she should know. I pointed out that the insole was some different flat for one..she didn't care..she loves the red color. This may be the first pair of man-made material ones she's had so I'll see how she likes them as time goes and she has wore them all day..which she will because of the events she will be attending wearing them.
The tags inside or on the box do not specify leather or man-made..there is a small white sticker in one shoe on the sole that says man-made uppers.
I myself have a longing for the glove leather..maybe the white or black princess is still that lovely leather and the smell of leather and not the rank stench of this synthetic shoe...the stench does go away with some airing out...but still looks and feels fake.

title: like military kinds found on Amazon
text:
These socks are exactly what one would expect for the money. They are average wool socks that fit to size, keep the feet warm, but beginning piling and stretching quickly after laundering.

I live in the far north of the Midwest where it gets bitter cold during the winter. I wear these as my daily socks in a pair of Gore-Tex lined hiking boots. Even in the coldest weather, these do the trick for me. My feet are warm when outside and if I put on a pair of slippers inside, my feet will sweat. With properly dry boots or shoes, these will keep the feet warm. I've no experience with them when wet.

If wearing a larger pair of boots, such as calf-length Muck boots, these work well with a pair of thin, knee-high, wool boot liners, like military kinds found on Amazon. Put the liners on first, and then these. Without the liners, the socks tend to fall down around the ankles in high boots, making them a pain to wear when hiking, snowshoeing, or other mobile activities.

The issue here is not one of warmth or price, but one of durability. I own seven or eight different brands of wool socks and sock systems for various activities, including many outdoor winter sports. These are the least durable socks so far (but also the cheapest). The next closest comparison are some Browning 77% wool blend socks. They cost a little more but have held up much better over many years. These People's socks have already started degrading after just one winter season. If you plan to replace them regularly, then they are a great purchase.

Another issue of quality is the hold. The tops just don't hold well after several uses and begin to slide down even under normal, daily wear. If you hate wool socks that fall down to your ankles, be warned, these are likely to do that -- I own eight pair, all do that.

Launder them carefully according to instructions as improper laundering will likely degrade the socks even faster.

title: Great for everyday and possibly very light climbing.
text:
They're okay... It's been a few months now, break in is terrible at first but then the boot becomes really comfortable to WALK/WORK in but as far as climbing, I can't say that I am impressed... I was transferred to a backyard crew and had to climb everyday, all day and it was extremely painful for my feet, the leg iron would even leave the arch during climbing (yes, it was strapped and tight..).

That said, my other coworkers highly recommend these... These are probably the most popular boots for linemen.

Great for water as well, I coated these with that hoffman bee dressing and now I can comfortably submerge the ENTIRE boot without any water getting through (trust me, I've done it for minutes at a time).

title: Good fit, a little thin - Not ideal for long hikes or backpacking
text:
Great value for the money. I have ordered two rounds of these: first round were pretty thick in the foot area. Second round almost seemed like a slightly different sock, they are noticably thinner in the foot (especially on the bottom). But with 4 pairs of socks in a pack, even if you put two socks on each foot to stay extra warm or to backpack 20 miles, it's STILL a good deal. They come up pretty darn high on my ankles, so it's perfect for treking through brush and stuff. I wear them throughout the summer and my feet stay pretty dry. Pretty good bang for the buck.
Update 3/24/2016: I bought a third round of these and to reduce the rating down to a 3. First round I got was great. Second was "just OK". The third batch i got are VERY THIN, almost like the "formula" has been changed. They are already wearing through in the heels. These are OK for wearing as an alternative to "dress socks" or for casual walking around, but these are NOT HIKING SOCKS. I certainly wouldn't take these ones on a backpacking trip. I'd recommend spending a little more money and get a proper set of hiking socks that are thick, can take a beating, and won't lose their form.

title: They look and feel great! Unfortunately my little toe swelled up and was ...
text:
They look and feel great!
Unfortunately my little toe swelled up and was super itchy after just one full day of wearing these boots, not sure if, the swollen toe and the boots are related?
I stopped wearing new boots and am treating toe for athletes foot. Once toe is back to being good after a week or so will try the new boots again & see if, the boots had anything to do with the swollen/ itchy toe? I'm concerned that the new boots maybe sealed up to tight and feet can't breath but, don't know for sure, It's too early to tell. Boots are very comfortable right out of the box so, I'm hoping to be able to wear them daily soon.
I'd give them five stars if, turns out swollen toe has nothing to do with boots chemicals or design.
Thanks-

title: Great Boots With One Large Caveat
