The only caveat and the only reason theyâ€™re not 5 stars for me is the fact the seam in the picture on the inside of of the boot digs into my foot super hard. Obviously this will go away as the boots are broken in and the extended break in time is due to the thicker nature of full grain leather. However, it is still painful and I havenâ€™t yet been able to make it through a full workday wearing the boots. Hopefully this will clear up in a week or two because otherwise the boots are very comfortable.

title: Holds On To Sweat, But It Works
text: Works pretty well. It definitely seems to run large. Occasionally sweat will find it's way down my sleeve and create a few sweat spots under my arms if the pads become completely saturated, and trust me, I completely saturate them. The other downside to that is the sweat doesn't evaporate away, so you're left with a gross, cold, soaked feeling all day. The shirt will stay soaked for several days after you take it off and put it in the laundry. I'd recommend buying more than one. I'll definitely get the deep v-neck one next to hide the shirt when I'm wearing polos. Sometimes the sleeves do stick out of polo shirts, so I'm also planning on ordering a size smaller and wearing it more like a compression shirt, to hide the shirt as much as I can.

title: sizing is a little small, but product works as specified -- and works good!
text: I ordered the XL, its' the size I usually wear in shirts. It fits, but it is a little smaller than what I am used to (but it is functional as an undershirt, no doubt. if you prefer a little more room, I suggest ordering a size up. I work at a job where I sweat exorbitant amounts. When I wear this shirt, I have absolutely no pit stains or "leakage" from the pads. After washing, the shirt and the pads feel the same and don't bunch or shrink. Remember that a shirt can only do so much; one might have hyperhidrosis if they are sweating through this shirt, and they should probably see a doctor so that the issue can be addressed.

title: wolverine boots have tight safety toe area
text: The Wolverine overpass safety toe boot is a pretty comfortable boot overall. It did take a few weeks of wearing them to break-in. However did not wear every day, used them on for two off for one. This is my second pair of wolverines with safety toe, and both pairs have been a little snug up in toe area to the point of some discomfort after 8-10 hrs of use. The boot itself feels good otherwise, nice lace-up feature, some what of a soft spring in sole and waterproof design. If they could make toe area a bit wider with the composite or steel toe design it would be a 5 star boot for me. I did order a "wide" in my size.

I think that they use the internet as a way of getting rid of their clothing that they could not otherwise sell in a brick and mortar store. Small thigs like the pockets are sometimes sewn in the wrong place, like almost under your armpit. And the thread on the hem at the waistline always comes undone. Something was wrong with the neck too, it was like I had the shirt on backwards, but it wasn't. I love Carhartt clothing, but I don't think I'm going to by them on-line anymore.

title: Good, but quality is slipping
text:
This is the third pair I have purchased in the last 15 years. As usual, one of the boots needs it's snaps repaired right out of the box (which is no big deal in my case because I have spare snaps and a snap-setting anvil). However, I have noticed with each successive pair I have purchased since 2004ish, the overall quality keeps slipping farther and farther....like the employees or corporate managers are caring less and less over time. The stitching is less exact, the quality of the leather is lesser (and perhaps a bit thinner, especially on the snap-flaps). Another gripe I have is that the old fabric tags that they used to sew into these had classy, old-timey font and and a little American Flag embroidered onto them; the new ones are flimsy, cheap, and look like they were designed by a design-school dropout.
In spite of these sort of things, these boots are still superior than most boots coming out of China, and I will continue to buy them; however, I can only give them 4 stars now. Also, I can tell you from experience that the 985's with the Vibram-style sole will vastly outlast the same model with the flat, jump-style soles (though these can be resoled in any case).

title: Super comfortable for 10+ hour days
text:
I have searched high and low for a comfortable boot and I finally found it! I used to wear the Nike Special Field Boots but the dole eventually started to detach (after 4+ years of wear!). I liked them because they were super lightweight, felt like running shoes, and werenâ€™t super thick around my ankle. When I tried to reorder them, they must of changed something because I could never get the right fit. Which, after trying 3 other types of boots, led me to these Danners.

I tried the Danner Acadia in the past and they were too clunky and thin (I have wide feet) but read the reviews of these boots, as they seemed similar to my beloved Nikes, and I was not disappointed. They are super comfy, have a wide toe box, lace up easy, and arenâ€™t clunky in the ankle area. The only complaint I would have is when I lace them up, the tongue of the shoe is too thin width wise and doesnâ€™t always sit flush when I lace my shoes up so Iâ€™m not sure how that would work in a waterproof environment. Otherwise, I love them and would by them again in the future.

Also, theyâ€™re made in the USA!

title: Thick, warm socks
text:
These are the ONLY socks my husband wears in the fall and winter. He wears the shorter ones (with shorts) in the fall and the crew socks in the cold, winter months. I wear the women's too, and we both like them. They are thick, warm and super cushion-y. Our feet to seem to sweat with these socks either, which is great.

They wash and dry really well and hold their shape. They will pill (after a very long while of washing/drying/wearing) ~ I would say after at least one season of constant wearing. The only complaint *I* have, is that they are a bit tight around my calves (again, that review will be under the women's crew socks). These socks also stay in place, and don't crawl down. Highly recommend People socks!

I may be allergic to the wool, my feet kind of itched and felt a little too warm/burning sensation. But that isn't the sock's fault. Overall, I'd say they were a good purchase, price was better than others for the quality.

title: New stock comes with Velcro adjuster & fit XL heads!
text:
I bought one of these hats elsewhere with the metal buckle adjuster & it wouldn't come close to fitting my XL (motorcycle helmet size) head.

I returned it & contacted the seller - they told me they used to come with the metal buckle adjuster, but about a year ago the manufacturer changed & went to the Velcro adjuster - what you get will depend on how old the stock is that is shipped to you.

I took a chance & ordered from Amazon - it came with the Velcro adjuster & fits my XL head with some room to spare, so I ordered a 2nd one (also had the Velcro adjuster).

I'd probably give it 5 stars, but it appears to me that the hat body itself could be just a little larger, and I do have to flatten out the brim somewhat as it comes with a heckuva bow in it.

title: Good product good customer service.
text:
Loved the original product, solid, comfortable, trendy boot.

**update**

The sole started separating from the boot at the toe out of no where. I donâ€™t wear
these to work. They r a street boot that is taken care of. I contacted Thorogood reference the 1 year warranty. They said they would honor the warranty but would prefer i contact the original seller. I located the original seller off amazon and made contact. The customer service staff were very polite. They located my info on amazon, gave me simple directions on how to return my defective product. I was required to purchase postage to return the defective boot to them which Iâ€™m not accustomed to as it was through amazon prime and with any issue i usually receive free return status. It cost approximately $20. This was the only issue i had however. I believe the turn around on the time i sent the defective boots to the time the replacement boots were on my front step was a week. The customer service agent was in contact with me via email the entire time. Pretty good experience overall. New boots r beautiful. I would not be afraid to purchase more boots from this seller. I gotta take a star off for the defective sole. If the soles woulda separated after my year warranty was up i woulda been responsible to have them fixed my self. A $200 dollar boot with gentle
Use should have a longer warranty or not have these issues.

title: Very cozy socks at a great price, even if they are kind of ugly
text:
These socks fit great and have the thickness and fluff you'd expect from wool socks.

Despite being fairly thick socks, I don't feel they negatively impact shoe fit. Shoe fit is a wee bit tighter with People Socks than with Smart Wool or generic white socks, but not detrimentally so. YMMV if your shoes fit super tight with thinner socks.

My four-pack has been through the wash maybe five times or so by now, and the socks are holding up well. I do get little bits of rolled wool lint coming off these after tumbling through the dryer, but the quality overall hasn't been significantly impacted by this. Still, it's a bit of a cause for worry, as these aren't cheap socks. I wonder how they'll hold up after a hundred washes and beyond...

While a four-pack of these socks is definitely pricey compared to generic white cotton socks, these compare favorably in price to other brands of Merino Wool socks. Price is what attracted me to these socks in the first place--no joke at something like 50% the cost of Smart Wool.

The comfort factor is definitely there, too. The thickness of these socks provides some great padding when worn with shoes, and the wool fabric keeps your feet dry and cool. If you're a first time wool buyer and are worried that the socks will be too warm in winter, don't worry! They aren't too warm at all, despite the thickness. These be some cozy socks.

I also really don't like the in-your-face branding. The PS logo is on both sides of the ankle of the sock, and the "PEOPLE SOCKS" font across the foot is only on the left side. People not familiar with the brand might be able to make out part of the writing (since the words start near the toe of the sock) and interpret it as "PEOPLE SUCK". The PS logos on the ankle are also awfully less than stylish and don't hold a candle to Smart Wool's more aesthetically pleasing stick figure logo. The branding on this product is a real eye sore.

Overall 4 stars out of 5.

Pros: Comfort, price (compared to other leading wool sock sellers)
Cons: Ugly branding, concerns about durability

title: So far, so good...
text:
Ok, so I'm one big lunch away from 350 lbs so I go through boots like it's my job. Unfortunately, It isnt. My job does however put my boots through a lot. I walk a lot, I climb a lot and my boots are almost always wet. I work in the the brutally cold/snowy winters and the scorching summer heat. I've killed Timberland Pro boots in 3 months. They started leaking just before 90 days.

These are going on 4 months with no leaking. They seem to be holding up just fine so far and even look new every day I put them away. Granted, I rinse them off at the end of each shift because of the stuff I work around.

These boots are very light weight compared to anything I've worn in the past. With this lack of weight comes lack of padding, especially at the ball of the foot. I immediately went out and purchased insoles because I could feel the rocks I walked over at work and it wasn't very pleasant. I think I should have gotten a wide because my toes can sometimes feel a little bunched in together so I might try that next time.

Thats all I've got for now. 4 months in. We'll see how things play out.

title: Helps my feet stay warm!
text:
I have poor circulation in my feet, so I decided to look for a sock which would keep my feet warmer, but that I could wear on an everyday basis, year round. These socks are great, and much warmer than standard cotton socks. I'm pretty happy with the cost:quality ratio here, and plan to be a returning customer.
One word of caution, these will pill if you put them in a normal drying load. I'd hang-dry them if you have the time/space to do so.

title: Fulfills its purpose
text:
I'm a heavy perspire-er who exacerbates it with lots of water and lots of caffeinated drinks. For years I have selected shirts in white, dark colors, and/or synthetic fabrics solely because I know that bright colors and cotton tend to darken considerably when wet.

I didn't have super high hopes for this, but I'll say, it does meet my needs for day-to-day usage. I can wear one of these shirts to work and not worry about wet underarms. I can also wear dress shirts without the underarms getting wet.

There are 3 things I want to mention though:
1. This shirt works by absorbing your sweat. IT DOES NOT MAGICALLY STOP SWEATING. This means that throughout the day, I feel wet fabric against my underarms. The first few times I wore this I kept checking my underarms because I couldn't believe that the moist feeling didn't equate to sweaty pits, but it worked.
2. I have only worn this shirt indoors at around 68-70 degrees. I cannot imagine the absorption would work in very hot/humid environments or when doing exercise. If I walked around in hot weather for a while I'm sure my sweat would soak through the underarms.
3. These shirts run very large. I typically wear a size large t-shirt for comfort, or a size medium t-shirt if I'm going for a very fitted look. I ordered a medium here and it's baggy on me. I will likely order small in the future.

title: I love these Oakley Holbrooks - wide for my fat head
text:
This will be my 3ed pair in the last 7-years. I love these Oakley Holbrooks - wide for my fat head. After time, the lenses will start to delaminate along the edges around the frame (thus the 4 star ratting) ---> You would think that with ALL the testing videos I've seen Oaken make they could do something about that (?!). Anyway, with the past two pair, after a year or so, I replaced the lenses by a seller on Amazon - I actually like the aftermarket lenses better...go figure. The frame holds up very well and I'm not a gentle guy. They go on sale all the time - don't pay over $79 - just keep watching them from time to time and bingo! WARNING: Other people like them more than you so don't leave them unattended or you'll be on your 3ed pair too.
Cheers

title: Cool boots need to be broken in
text: These boots are very cool. Good quality leather, stitching seems to be solid, brass hardware looks great and put on solid. I ordered a size 10 and they have a bit of room in them on the heel. Two pairs of socks or thick wool winter socks should take care of this. I would return them for a 9.5 but they seem to have less room in the toe and I don't want that any tighter. There is a comfortable, removable,  shock absorbing insole that should do nicely for those times that I'm on my feet all day. Out sole is non slip and put on solid. The only gripe I have is there seems to be a bit of the boot pressing down on my big toe quite sharply. I think over time with some good breaking in this will subside. Until then I will use a thicker sock to provide a bit of cushion. Very cool, very unique boots that you don't see every day and are sure to get a lot of compliments.

There is a comfortable, removable,  shock absorbing insole that should do nicely for those times that I'm on my feet all day. Out sole is non slip and put on solid. The only gripe I have is there seems to be a bit of the boot pressing down on my big toe quite sharply. I think over time with some good breaking in this will subside. Until then I will use a thicker sock to provide a bit of cushion. Very cool, very unique boots that you don't see every day and are sure to get a lot of compliments.

title: Great for hiking and cooler weather
text:
Got these for a cold fall weather multi-day hiking trip where I actually had to worry about my weight and how much of vital clothing to bring or repeat (underwear, socks in particular). I heard about the magic of good wool socks and convinced myself to buy these. I can attest that they definitely don't get as stinky as cotton or synthetic over multiple uses, though when a bit moist, they do exude the distinctly wet wool odor---not bad, but not my favorite.
They are warm too, which is good for warmer weather, though not sure how i'd react if it were late spring or summer. Might be too warm for that. For 50 degrees and under they are really great.

title: Beautifully crafted. Perfect size for modern slim jeans.
text:
Got this because my old (Saddleback) wallet was a little too big for my selvedge jeans. This wallet is the PERFECT size to slide in with ease and have just enough room for comfort without falling out (jeans are Naked & Famous, for reference). Pictures shown with 6 cards and 5 bills. Great fit and finish. Cognac is a color prewear, wish it had a bit more vibrancy though.

The 2 drawbacks from this are 1) the mentioned lack of vibrancy in color and 2) the leather texture lacks softness and has a treated feel to it. For the price, I am happy with what I got but left me wanting a touch more. But I would still recommend their products to anyone looking.

title: Pretty good for the price.
text:
I have really wide feet and high arches and it's hard for me to get a good fit a lot of the time. I wear a 9.5 EEE in the Allen Edmonds 65 last, 9.5 E in Alden barrie, if that means anything to you. Bought these in 9.5 Wide. When I first put them on they were too snug around the ball of my foot, but after doing the laces really loose at the bottom and about a three day a break-in period my freakish feet are comfortable in them. The side zip feature is really good though; once you get them laced right you can just skip into them without having to redo it every time.

The length is perfect and they have a lot of toe room. I was hoping they'd be padded a bit more, but they're comfy enough to hike a couple miles in. They're definitely good for work, tactical operating and kicking fascists.

My only concern is that the leather feels a little plasticy. It says it's full grain but I think it's actually corrected grain. For an under $200 boot I'm not really that disappointed, though.

title: Not the longest lasting, but they kept my feet WARM!
text:
I am a size 10 shoe and these fit fairly well. They are not snug as you expect cotton socks to be, but this is how wool socks typically are. They really do help keep my feet warm and they even stay warm when they get a little wet - unlike cotton.

The only thing that prevents a 5 star review is they didn't last that long. They lasted about six-seven months before they had holes in them. If you're an active person they may wear out even sooner. I suppose it may depend on the type of insole liners you have as well.

Fortunately they are cheap enough that 6 months is an OK time line.

The next pair I bought from Sams called "Omni wool" They seem like they may last longer and are more elastic (comfortable) but don't seem to keep my feet as warm as these People Socks did. I will probably buy these again as soon as my OmniWool socks wear out.

title: Like it, Waiting to Love it
text:
I have worn Red Wing 875's for six years, and I loved them. I work in commercial construction, so boots are important. The price tag, and good reviews made me purchase these Thorogood boots.

1) The run large. I just bought running shoes Brooks size 13 EE, and I fit in a 11.5 EE in Thorogood. Good thing that there are free returns, so you can get the sizing right.
2) The brown model is suede. I am a little concerned about their weather resistance, but the color is nice.
3) The boots are very comfortable. They have a lot of cushioning, and it only took two days to break-in, while my Red Wings took two weeks. I am a little concerned about how the cushioning will hold up. They cushioning could degrade.

There are not problems with these boots, but I am waiting to officially switch my allegiance. I have had the boots for three weeks; we'll have to see my sentiment in a year.

title: Very good product, meets realistic expectations
text:
Great product! Had realistic expectations and this product met them. No odors and you do not have to wash them after every use. The tee reminds me of my Hanes t-shirts; the water absorbtion material under the armpits are hardly noticible and are instantly forgoton about. If you plan on wearing them daily, you will need to purchase at least 3 unfortunately($) to alternate because they take a while to completely dry. I have purchased two of them over the last month. Only once did sweat seep through (minimal if even barely noticiable) In the products defence, this is why I said you need to purchase multiple if it is going to be an everyday wear. I believe the only reason it failed on the one occasion is because it was still slightly damp from the day prior.
Tip: Hang them inside out in a dry non-humid location after use or washing.

title: Great shoe tree; worth it over cheaper alternatives
text:
I purchased both these and the ones made by Footfitter based on customer review. I wanted to see if there was a difference; after all, a shoe tree is a shoe tree, right?

The Allen Edmonds brand is both of better quality and fits the shoe much better. Feeling around these sides near the toe, I can feel the support throughout vs. the other brand. In fact, I ended up buying 2 more pairs of the Allen Edmonds for my nicer shoes. I'll use the Footfitter ones for cheaper shoes.

I'd recommend spending a few extra bucks to get these over the cheaper ones, especially for nicer shoes. If you are going to drop $300+ on nice shoes, it's worth it to get better quality shoe trees to help them last even longer.

title: Very nice socks
text:
Very nice socks. Much heavier/thicker than I thought, making them an even greater value. I like the extra cushion it provides. I have been a long time user of merino wool socks, wearing them daily. I usually order them on sale from Sierra Trading Post, and my favorite brands are Goodhew, Brookdale, and Lorpen. Generally I go with a medium weight hiking sock, but I have bought some heavy weight as well. My experience has been that the higher the percentage of wool, the less wear I get out of the sock. I'm finally convinced that a good blend with synthetics is the better for durability. I will update my review after I wear these and see how they hold up with washing and wear. For durability, Goodhew has been my gold standard, although I think Brookdale has the nicest fit, generally with a design that puts the synthetics in an elastic form in specific locations, which doesn't do much to improve heel wear.

Why merino wool? I spend some of my time in the rural mountains, and the merino wool sock gives me the protection I need from blisters, is cool in summer and warm in winter and is soft as a kitten. My favorite thing is that you can wear them wet. I generally only have to pack an extra pair, even for several days. I can take a little soap and water and wash them out, wring well, and air dry, or even put them on and let them dry on my feet.

I would give them a 5 star overall rating except that after a lot of use, the underarm pads retain odor you cannot wash out.  I would suggest that they use a Microbial fabric in the built-in under-arm pads to prevent this - - - - however,  I get a 2 year service life out of the shirts before this starts to happen, which in my book is great for the convenience they provide.

title: Nearly Red Wing Killers!
text:
Like many of you, I was agonizing over the purchase of my first pair of Red Wing boots until I stumbled across these Thorogood Moc Toe Boots. I spent time in a Red Wing store trying on multiple pairs of their different styles and loved most of them. But, I just couldn't pay the price. Don't get me wrong, I actually think they are worth it. But I "shouldn't" afford them.

So on to find something similar. Not only are these Thorogood's similar, they are nearly identical and a stunning value.

The initial fit is a little different than RW. I have some minor heel slippage on day one. Sounds like that is a good thing and will disappear as they break in.

The quality of the leather and stitching is wonderful. Softer than the RW's but no less thick and substantial. I have no worries about these lasting. The wedge soles are indeed a Thorogood product and they feel great.

I like the subtle ways the Red Wing's look in comparison, but not twice the price worth! However, that little "Made in the USA" tag has got to go.

I ordered 2 sizes since there is no half size between 12 and 13. They certainly run large. You really have to order a 1/2 or full size down. Especially if you are on the fence between two sizes. The 12's will likely break into a perfect fit for me. I'll update this review as they do so.

title: Like coming home
text:
At the age of 17 I got my first job with the AH Weinbrenner Shoe Co, in my home town of Marshfield, WI. It was a summer job and, as I recall I was only allowed to work 30 hr / week, being a minor. I earned $0.85 /hr. This was back in 1957. A couple of years later, the factory in Marshfield closed as the company fell upon hard times. My life went in other directions and I essentially forgot the experience. Then, a few weeks ago I stumbled upon the brand name "Thorogood" while on Amazon, and realized that my old employer was back in business, and had been for some time..the employees having bought out the original company. Back in the day I had only seen a small part of the shoe making process; my job that summer was to glue fabric pads onto the sole inner-liners. I remember the smell of the glue, the sight of stacks and stacks of glued-up inner-liners and the boasting of my permanent employee companions that they were paid for piece-work while I had to be content with a straight hourly wage.

With my final paycheck that summer, I bought a pair of Thorogood work boots (as seconds) from the company store. I think I paid something like $12 or so, more than a full day's wage.

The boots I bought then were a box toe style and of tan color, these are moc toe and black. It's not as if I really need work boots of this quality at this point in my life, but hey, I just couldn't resist. Any yes, I'm keeping the little flags on them.

title: Fulfilled Expectations
text:
I wore these shoes out for the first time today and I had not anticipated the attention I would get ! Like many women in my age group, have mixed memories of these saddle shoes of our youth. What was a reliable shoe decades ago, is now a fun and attractive remembrance of days passed. A few young girls told me they were now "in" and several ladies in the 55-60 age range stopped me to say "are those saddle shoes!" I knew I would enjoy wearing them but the unexpected comments were an addition.
As far as the shoe itself, I found it to be very comfortable. I wore them for about 8 hours and was not in any hurry to take them off. They look just as
pictured. There's lots of comments about sizing in the reviews and I was quite confused what size to order. Depending on the shoe I range from a 7.5 to an 8. Some said size up, some said size down. I went with the 8 and they fit great. I'm pleased treated myself to this throw back

title: This Person likes the People Socks!
text: Been cycling through a dozen pairs of these socks for 2 yrs as my primary sock both Winter and Summer. After two yrs I have noticed â€œ1â€ of the dozen has a hole in a non critical area (darn it!). I wear them usually with large hiking style boots, currently Timberlands... I point that out to say that I always flip the top of my sock down over the top of my boots to hold my laces down, probably you wonâ€™t but I want to illustrate that the Top elastic has held up with this practice just fine. I machine wash with Tide Pods, AND machine dry every time with minimal shrinking after 2 yrs. The shrinking just makes it feel like Iâ€™m putting on new socks after each wash. Socks provide amazing warmth and comfort in the Winter and make great run around the house socks on cold nights. In summer I can wear them on warm/hot days with minimal discomfort, but even on the hottest days they wick moisture from my feet and keep them feeling and smelling great. I often wear these socks for 2 days straight between washing and have had no problems with smell or durability (occasionally that will be 3 days) so fear not only taking a couple pairs camping and hiking.

title: Very thick, warm socks
text:
These are very thick socks! I purchased these for my husband to use for boots when hunting and also for cold nights when he complains about being cold. He loved them.

I even tried them out for a night when it was chilly. Of course they were too big for my feet (woman's size 7.5), but they did keep my feet warm and worked great on my cold tile floor keeping my feet cozy.

Keep in mind these are very thick so you need to wear shoes that would allow for the extra bulk. Also, wash in cold water and allow to air dry. If you put these in the dryer they will shrink. They do dry very fast though.

This was a great purchase and bargain for 4 pairs of socks of such great quality. I would definitely recommend these for wearing with boots, lounging around or sleeping on cold nights.

title: AO Original Pilot Military Sunglasses (Chrome,57mm)
text:
These are the real McCoy! Don't fall prey to imitations. The lenses in these glasses are engineered to give "true color" and they do! They are crystal clear with no imperfections. The matte nickel, bead blasted frames are most attractive and do not reflect light. The temple braces fit snugly to the head and do not cause pressure on the ears like regular sunglasses. I have several other pilot's glasses including Ray Ban's and the AO's are much more comfortable when worn for long periods.

Overall, I don't see a need to spend a lot of $$ on fashion sunglasses that aren't for real. If you are a pilot, these will be your favorites. They make cloud formations stand out nicely.

title: Excellent material and comfort
text: I'm pretty blown away by this top...it's versatile enough to lounge around the house, a light walk, yoga or for other casual days.  I even wear it to bed.  I was really excited to see this high end brand is now sold on Amazon.  The material is superb quality, it's soft as can be and feels SO comfortable against my skin. It also allows my skin to breath, which I love.  I also absolutely love that it has a built in bra.  It's not a push up bra - it's casual, more like a bralette.  I found it to run pretty true to size, there's plenty of room in the mid section and it hangs sort of flowy - not clingy at all.  If you fluctuate between two sizes, you're most likely safe to go with the smaller of the two.

title: American Made
text: I have just received my Thorogood boots and have been wearing them for a couple of hours. Out of the box they looked very well made and I particularly like the made in the USA tab sewn onto them. The fit is true to the size I normally wear (12) and after only wearing them for this short period of time they are quite comfortable. They are not lined or padded as previous boots I have worn but still feel soft and not stiff at all. I have worn many different brands of boots (Red Wing, Danner, Chippewa, Georgia, Justin, Timberland to name a few) and to his point I thought that the Red Wings were the best, but at a price. This same boot from Red Wing would be more than twice the price of these and I don't believe they are any better, just more expensive. I generally destroy a pair of boots in about six months so this would mean I would spend $200 as compared to about $500. When you think of it in those terms, doesn't make much sense to spend that much more. I would recommend these boots for quality, price and comfort at this point. Time will tell if they stand up after a few months of construction trade torture.

title: These Are Great Socks
text: We do a lot of cruise vacations that are two weeks plus in length.  There is no argument that cotton is the most comfortable garment for me. But, doing laundry on a cruise is expensive or takes valuable personal time.  Air drying cotton clothing in a hotel or on a ship takes days.  So, I have rediscovered the value of synthetic fabrics for my shirts (like â€œDri-Tekâ€ material) and rip-stop polyester pants.  Socks were the next challenge.  Thatâ€™s where I discovered these â€œPeople Socks Unisex Merino Wool Antimicrobial Crew Socksâ€.  We just finished a very active three cruise and these socks were great.  They are very comfortable in all kinds of weather.  My feet never got hot or cold on long hikes and walks with outside temperature from 40 to 85 degrees.  At night I just washed them in the sink with shampoo (I figured they are hair, so, why not) squeezed out the excess water with a towel and hung them to dry.  The next morning, they were completely dry and ready for the next dayâ€™s adventure.  I highly recommend these socks!

title: Life changing
text: I was extremely skeptical of this product initially. As I have an issue called hyperhidrosis, as I would suspect most people looking at this review might have as well. I will quite literally sweat in the snow with a T-shirt on. I have had used several different medications including the prescription and OTC strength Drysol, and a fair new prescription drug Qbrexza which have all been approved for hyperhidrosis. They didn't work as hoped. I'd even ware under armour shirts to help reduce the sweat. Even in combination, nothing worked. So my trust was quite low initially. When I got these shirts I was about to go to Vegas for a conference in hopes of getting a residency when I graduate college. So needlessly to say I was stressed and that will cause me to sweat even more. Absolutely, NO SWEAT was shown through my dress shirts, and even T-shirts. If I ever meet the creator of this product I will buy him/her a steak dinner, as it has boosted my confidence that I won't be sweating so much that I could fill a pool. If you are hesitant, about this product I get it. Just know if it worked for me It will work for you.

title: Sizing Issues - Know your Workboot size...

The overboots themselves are great. Pull all you want, they will stretch right over most of the boots you are wearing. Snug, secure, comfortable, and will last as long as several pairs of the cheap PVC boots. That's time saved going back to the supply warehouse. That is unless you have some oversized work boots to go into them.

With most of my standard sized boots (Wolverine, Bass, etc) in 13W (approx 13 to 13-1/4" sole length), these slip on and off just fine.

The problem is with my Thorogood 13W steel Moc toe wedge boot, which is a copy of a Red Wing 1907. I think Thorogood simply used their sz 14 lasts to make these, as the sole measures 13-7/8" from end to end (rolling the ruler along the sole). The steel Moc toes simply add to the bulk.

The day I decided to get a pair of these (based on recommendations), I was wearing my smaller-soled Wolverines boots. I placed my boot on the measuring display on the side of the box, as well as the Treds measuring decal on the floor at the building supply store, and the measurement showed my boots were well under the max measuring line to use the L/XL sized overboots (odd choice for a boot size, since they also have an XL and XXL). The store didn't carry the XL or XXL, and I knew of only one other store in the county that carried this brand of overboots. Thought they would fit the same on all of my boots. After a couple of uses, though, I realize they just aren't going to work with the larger-soled Thorogood boots, as I discovered when I tried the overboots on them later.

I love the Thorogood work boots; it's just that they're too big to fit into these overboots without a ton of effort to get them on and are nearly impossible to get off once forced on. I went back to the supply store and compared the Thorogood boots to the measuring display on the floor and box, and they came up just a hair width below the max measuring line for the L/XL size.

I will look for the XL, one size up, for use with these boots or other Moc toe / steel toe boots, on the off chance they too are oversized. Wasn't really planning on getting two pairs, but thats what I am going to have to do. Fortunately, I will get plenty of use out of these pouring concrete, whichever workboots I'm wearing.

At the Treds.com website (I discovered after the fact), they have a sizing chart (not available at the retailer I went to; they only had the put-your-shoe-on-the-line sticker on the floor, plus the measuring marks on the product box). The chart shows that a sole length of 13 1/4 - 13 3/4" should use the L/XL, 13 3/4 - 14 1/2" should use XL, and 14 1/2 - 15 1/2" should use XXL. Wish I had that info before I purchased the smaller pair. Now I will end up with two pairs.

Finding the XL version here at Amazon takes a bit of work, though. A standard "Treds over shoe / boot" search doesn't show the XL model in the results. The seller who markets most of the other sizes here doesn't advertise the XL, and it is instead listed at Amazon under another title... "Treds XL Over the Shoe 17" Slush Boot", part number 17853, ASIN B001I014I8.

If you wear longer 13's or 14's workboots, or larger, definitely try these on for size if possible, because they may not fit well.

Note: These are not lined. I didn't find that a problem. Just thick, solid stretchy rubber.

Update: Received the XL sized overboots, and they work perfectly with the larger workboots. Just FYI.

title: and wanted them to be easy to step into and get off
text: I purchased these to wear on the farm for light chores when I don't want to wear a full-on boot but need waterproofing, and wanted them to be easy to step into and get off, which they are.  Very nicely made with quality materials and nice detailing, like the little integrated hooky thingy on the back of the heel so you can use you other boot to pull the other boot off; the fabric collar for comfort and sealing out the elements; the ergonomic design for comfort.  As several reviewers suggested I ordered up to the next whole size since I am a half size - good decision. However, because of that and the fact that I have narrow feet, I purchased and installed under the existing insert a sole insert which took care of the slightly "too wide" feeling, as well as the tendency for the heel to slip when walking at a fast pace and pivoting. Actually, I am cheap so I bought a house brand "double thick foot pillow insole" and cut the heel part off. I love these especially because they are made in the USA <3

title: 2 years and still going strong
text:
I wear these socks in an operating room (which we like to keep very cold) and these have never failed to keep my feet warm and toasty. They retain heat very well and they don't get soggy or damp when you sweat (that's wool for you).

They also aren't so thick that you can't fit into your normal shoes which is nice (you might have to size up 1/2 size for some of the thicker brands). After 2 years these socks have some pilling (as to be expected) but no signs of breakage or holes yet. I expect these to last another year no problem.

title: Western boots actually still made in the west!!
text: I've always loved my Tony Lamas and my Ariats, but I don't like that they are made in China. So I've been going about looking for a new boot company that makes their boots here in the US. Abilene has not let me down. They are beautiful, well made and there was a nice selection (They had my blunt toes- not those pointy things, not the awful square toe, but the tapered blunt toe...YES!!). These boots have a comfortable lining that doesn't chaff my leg should my socks slide down and they were so easy to break in. I only had two days of soreness in that one spot at the ankles where leather overlaps. Now that's good. (I remember wearing duct tape over my socks with my Tony Lamas. Lol.) The only thing I wish they had were the little finger holes at the top, not that these boots are hard to put on or anything, I just like what I like. I highly recommend giving Abilene boots a shot. They deserve it for keeping the entegrity of the WESTERN boot.

title: Great Socks for 8 Eyelet Doc Martens 1460 Boots
text:
[[ASIN:B00A9MQCVK Hue Women's Mini Crew Sock 6-Pack, Black, One Size]]

I bought these because I needed more socks of a compatible height with my 8 eyelet Doc Martens 1460 boots. I didn't want ankle socks since I have a problem with my exposed Achilles spot rubbing against the inside of the boots as I'm walking which causes gnarly blisters. For my intended use, the height is absolutely perfect - pulled on, they come up to about 3/4 inch below the top of my boots.

There is a bit of padding to the entire bottom of the sock, but as others have said it's not excessive at all. The socks are thinner on top than on bottom. They're not paper thin all around, so if that's your preference you probably won't like these. They are a perfect thickness though, not super thick like hiking socks but not paper thin like ballet socks. They do lean more thin than thick.

The toe seam is probably my favorite part, it's really well designed so there are no awkward toe seam lumps to rub against your toes while you walk. In fact the seam is barely noticeable. And when you wear these, they don't slip or slide down from the top but they also don't feel like they have a stranglehold on your foot. They're like the goldilocks of socks. I'm a size 8 and these fit perfectly.

Overall would definitely buy again and would definitely recommend to others.

title: Comfortable hiking socks!
text:
I've finally had the chance to wear these on a couple of hikes, I wore one pair with Salomon gtx and my feet did not sweat like with other hiking socks, they offered the correct amount of cushioning and comfort and the best part is that they DID NOT itch.
I like to wear wool socks, but my feet always itch, not with these, these are awesome for hiking, I will wait for the temperature to cool where I live and will give them a try as everyday socks. I expect them to perform great.
The best part is that these are made here in the USA, and offer a great value for what I paid for 2 pairs, with other brands you will only get 1 pair at this price point, these are a bargain.

If you value your feet get these, I consider footwear the difference between a good day in the outdoors or a bad one. I will definitely buy more in the future.

Thompson, I was upset that you're on amazon.com and wanted to charge shipping unless $100+ purchase, when this should be "Prime" for Prime members, such as myself. It took 3 or 4 days to get to my door when "Prime" gets it to me in 2 or less.

title: Wow
text: I live in Arizona and I needed socks for the summer heat.  I had tried higher end synthetic workman socks and  running socks, but my feet would hurt and they would still get too sweaty.  Plus they would stink my car up after a round.  I had heard wool is the best but I always associated wool with heat and warmth.  However doing research Wool absorbs more water, breathes and evaporates quicker.  After my first round today in 100 degree heat I didn't even notice my feet the entire round.  These socks have so much more cushion, my feet were bone dry, and afterwards they don't even smell.  These are so comfy I'm actually going to swap out my normal socks and switch to 100% wool.  It is that big of a difference.

title: The everlasting sneaker.
text:
I purchased these shoes 7 months ago prior to starting an internship working with marine mammals. The past 7 months have really put this shoe to the test. Three or four months in, I watched as my peers' Nikes and New Balances fell apart. Five months in, the Adidas and Sketchers all started to go. My Reebok Princesses? Still going strong. Near the end of the sixth month, I had to superglue the left sole at the front. Other than that, they are holding together and still come out looking decent after a bleach-filled run through my washing machine. They have endured being soaked in freshwater, saltwater, cleaning solutions and being washed in the machine almost weekly. They have lasted me while every other interns shoes have fallen apart. Heck, they may be coming with me to my new position just because they're still going. Not pretty at this point, but still holding together.

So if you're looking for a sneaker that lasts, this is the way to go. They're not the most fashionable things I've ever put on my feet, but for $35 for shoes that have endured Shoe Hell for the past 7 months and worked fine the whole time, I can't complain too awful much. I definitely got my money's worth!
